sed analysts by saying its April sales rose 10 percent. Chrysler executives attributed the gain to a well-organized incentive program, including free DVD players in its minivans and discounts on the Dodge Ram pickup, as well as a successful 96-hour sale at the end of the month. “We were just very fortunate to catch the wind when we did in April,” said Steven J. Landry, Chrysler’s executive vice president for North American sales and global marketing. “We had a very strong close.” Meanwhile, Japanese automakers had an uncharacteristically weak month, with Honda’s sales down 1.6 percent and Nissan’s down 11.2 percent. Toyota posted a 3.7 percent sales increase, its lowest year-over-year gain since August 2004. Although Ford came in slightly ahead of it for the month, Toyota has sold nearly 5,000 more vehicles than Ford so far this year. Yet there are signs of some bumps in the road for Toyota, like an inventory that has grown 30 percent in the last year. Many of those unsold vehicles may be the new Tundra pickups; Toyota has sold about 43,000 Tundras since the truck went on sale in February, well below the pace needed to reach its goal of selling 200,000 this year. But because the Tundra makes more money for Toyota than the Edge does for Ford, the Edge cannot necessarily be called the more successful of the two. Still, Ford and its dealers say they are thrilled with the Edge. Mr. Pipas of Ford said it was competing well against crossover models from Toyota, Honda and Nissan. “The sales levels, really coming from having no brand recognition, are kind of in the same sandbox as three really great products that have established themselves over the course of several years,” Mr. Pipas said. “I don’t know if I thought we could get there that soon.” Ron Christiano, general manager of Cortese Ford in Rochester, said customers liked the Edge because it used less gas than an S.U.V. The Edge increased traffic to the dealership more quickly than Ford’s Fusion sedan, which has sold