ifornia, but according to Abdulla Essa, manager of the traffic department of Umm al Qaywayn, there has been a decrease in accidents among young drivers in the emirate over the last four years. The motorplex, which also has tracks for motocross and all-terrain vehicles, has an overwhelmingly local feel. These aren’t your average Pabst Blue Ribbon-drinking spectators — and it’s not simply because there’s no drinking allowed on the premises. PEOPLE: AUTO RACING; Daytona War Tribute Find New Cars » Find Used Cars » Explore Collectible Cars » Sell Your Car » De Contributor: Fliers and No Plan B Economix:
http://www.nytimes.com/2007/05/13/automobiles/13GREASE.html?ex=1336708800&en=4e763f215a8a4035&ei=5088&partner=rssnyt&emc=rss Where There&#8217;s Never an Oil Shortage - There’s Never an Oil Shortage Alan Zale for at Greasestock 2007 were not afraid to reveal their sources. 2007 Skip to next paragraph Alan Zale for solar car team from Newburgh Free Academy. Alan Zale for untrue to its name, Greasestock 2007 attracted a number of innovators who had gone beyond converting their vehicles to run on used fry oil. KARENA RUGGIERO, scrunched down in the cockpit of a tiny solar-powered racecar, never saw the small rock in the driveway of Peter Pratt’s Inn. But she knew it was there when the ground-scraping car — a brightly colored sliver with a wide bustle of photovoltaic cells splayed out behind — stopped dead in its tracks. So Ms. Ruggiero, a senior at the Newburgh Free Academy who had helped build the car, did what any savvy solar car racer would do: she bounced up and down in the seat to help inch the car forward. With a push from Jessica Marshall and Tova Markowitz, classmates who also helped with the car’s construction, the racecar gradually cleared the obstacle and continued on its way to the cheers of onlookers. This was Greasestock, the third annual gathering of “greasers,” people who have converted their diesel cars and trucks to run on vegetable oil. Somewhat untrue to its name, Greasestock 2007 attracted a number of innovators who had gone beyond converting their vehicles to run on used fry oil. In 2005, a tiny group — just eight committed aficionados — gathered at the invitation of Jon Pratt, the owner of the inn here in the rolling hills of northern Westchester County. By this year, attendance had grown to about 300 people, including nearly 50 who had driven converted vehicles. (I was among them, with my greased Jetta, which I have renamed Volksvegan.) Looking like a miniature county fair, the grounds of the inn were dotted with booths set up by local green businesses like ISI Solar and Choose Green Energy, two solar panel installers. But the biggest attraction for most attendees was the vehicles themselves, a collection of rather ordinary-looking Volkswagens and Mercedes-Benzes, along with a few Dodge and Ford trucks, lined up in the unpaved parking lot with their hoods raised. Brian Miller, who has driven more than 140,000 miles on used vegetable oil in his 1997 Ford F-250 pickup, made the 1,000-mile trip from his home in Peoria, Ill. “But you have to understand, I average 1,000 miles a week in my job, and it’s all on grease.” One of the more unusual cars was a bright green Austin Mini, modified with a Peugeot diesel engine and converted to run on vegetable oil. It was displayed by a Massachusetts company, Madhouse Minis. Some of the drivers had spent as little as $200 gathering up parts from hardware stores and plumbing suppliers; others had paid thousands of dollars for professional installation of components like a heated filter housing with electrically operated valves that automatically switch between tanks of diesel and vegetable oil. A crowd gathered as Wally Little, a partner in the newly formed V.O. Tech, a conversion company in nearby Mahopac, showed his filter unit, a shiny hunk of milled aluminum equipped with an electric heater to keep the normally viscous vegetable oil thin enough to pass through modern diesel injectors. At $1,250 for the custom-made device, he said, there’s barely a profit. A roaring sound drew a crowd of onlookers to a nearby oak tree, where Steve Leung was demonstrating another use for vegetable oil. On the ground in front of him were disembodied pieces of the oil-fired furnace that heats his home in Fairfield, Conn. A vigorous flame shot from the jet, showing that with the right adjustments, a furnace could be made to run on used cooking oil. “I thought of doing this last September, got it running in mid-October and heated my house all winter on vegetable oil,” Mr. Leung said. “I used about 700 gallons, and it was all free.” Mr. Pratt, who had closed his inn for the weekend to serve as host for the event, said he was happy to meet like-minded vegetable oil enthusiasts he had known only by their screen names at , an Internet meeting place established by one of the makers of conversion kits. Skip Wrightson, a customer service representative for Greasecar, the Massachusetts-based kit maker, said he saw vegetable oil conversions as a way “to establish a relationship with a car that allows people to live a modern life without doing damage to the earth.” Mr. Pratt expressed a different motive. “I run my car on grease to save money, and to not contribute to depending on foreign oil,” he said. “What it comes down to is I would just rather do it myself than depend on anyone else to provide fuel for my car.” Push More Use of Alternative Fuels Schwarzenegger Orders Cuts in Emissions On the Road Again, Where Biodiesel Is a Rising Star WHAT'S OFFLINE; How Many Miles to the Bushel? Find New Cars » Find Used Cars » Explore Collectible Cars » Sell Your Car » De Court Memo: Oral Dissents Give Ginsburg a New Voice on Court Comedy Business Turns to the Web Fiction and Lou Dobbs Lawmakers Push for Big Subsidies for Coal Process Google million dollar homes in Florida, Wyoming and California Also in Real Estate: U.S. Virgin Islands Home & Garden &#x00bb; Art & Design &#x00bb; Sarkozys: The French Kennedys? Phil Spector’s Long and Winding Road The Dirty Water Underground An Animated Film by Jeff Scher Artist Sets Up House(s) at the Grand Palais
http://www.nytimes.com/2007/05/13/automobiles/13GREASE.html?ex=1336708800&en=4e763f215a8a4035&ei=5088&partner=rssnyt&emc=rss Where There&#8217;s Never an Oil Shortage There’s Never an Oil Shortage Alan Zale for at Greasestock 2007 were not afraid to reveal their sources. 2007 Zale for solar car team from Newburgh Free Academy. Alan Zale for untrue to its name, Greasestock 2007 attracted a number of innovators who had gone beyond converting their vehicles to run on used fry oil. KARENA RUGGIERO, scrunched down in the cockpit of a tiny solar-powered racecar, never saw the small rock in the driveway of Peter Pratt’s Inn. But she knew it was there when the ground-scraping car — a brightly colored sliver with a wide bustle of photovoltaic cells splayed out behind — stopped dead in its tracks. So Ms. Ruggiero, a senior at the Newburgh Free Academy who had helped build the car, did what any savvy solar car racer would do: she bounced up and down in the seat to help inch the car forward. With a push from Jessica Marshall and Tova Markowitz, classmates who also helped with the car’s construction, the racecar gradually cleared the obstacle and continued on its way to the cheers of onlookers. This was Greasestock, the third annual gathering of “greasers,” people who have converted their diesel cars and trucks to run on vegetable oil. Somewhat untrue to its name, Greasestock 2007 attracted a number of innovators who had gone beyond converting their vehicles to run on used fry oil. In 2005, a tiny group — just eight committed aficionados — gathered at the invitation of Jon Pratt, the owner of the inn here in the rolling hills of northern Westchester County. By this year, attendance had grown to about 300 people, including nearly 50 who had driven converted vehicles. (I was among them, with my greased Jetta, which I have renamed Volksvegan.) Looking like a miniature county fair, the grounds of the inn were dotted with booths set up by local green businesses like ISI Solar and Cho