 including a divestiture. Mr. Zetsche insisted that Chrysler did not drain cash from Mercedes. Despite its recent losses, it generated nearly $15 billion in cumulative profits during the years it was owned by Daimler. But analysts said Daimler could have found better uses for the cash it poured into Chrysler. “They spent about $60 billion acquiring, restructuring and investing in Chrysler over the last nine years,” Mr. Jonas of Morgan Stanley said. “Just think where the next $60 billion could go if it was invested properly.” Among other things, he said, Mercedes-Benz could introduce more innovative and alluring cars to compete with German brands like BMW and Audi. BMW, which has taken the mantle of the world’s top luxury carmaker in recent years, may feel new heat from its old rival. on Verge of Sale to a Private Firm Cerberus&#8217;s Strategic Plan May Finally Be Paying Off Guardedly Kicking the Tires on Chrysler Again, Kerkorian Makes a Move for Chrysler Mergers, Acquisitions and Divestitures &#x00bb; MOST POPULAR - BUSINESS Bumped Fliers and No Plan B Economix: India, Grandma Cooks, They Deliver Is Wal-Mart Too Cheap for Its Own Good? Advertising: Telling India&#8217;s Modern Women They Have Power, Even Over Their Skin Tone Wachovia to Buy A.G. Edwards for $6.8 Billion Ernst & Young Won&#8217;t Face Criminal Charges Europe Pushes to Get Fuel From Fields Lens Fluid Maker Says Link to Infection Unsolved to See the Fallen Is No Favor The High Price of Creating Free Ads Apple's Lesson for Sony's Stores: Just Connect More Than Ever, It Pays to Be the Top Executive Is Wal-Mart Too Cheap for Its Own Good? Test of Drug for Diabetes in Jeopardy Now, Spitzer Is Warming to Wall St. Grandma Cooks, They Deliver a Complete Savings Acct from E*TRADE Bank
http://www.nytimes.com/2007/05/16/business/16auto.html?ex=1336968000&en=f50d88b169c93dbd&ei=5088&partner=rssnyt&emc=rss Auto Union Leader Finds Comfort Level - Union Leader Finds Comfort Level Jeff Kowalsky/European Pressphoto Agency Thomas W. LaSorda, Chrysler&#146;s chief, said he would keep using the services of a former Chrysler president. 2007 DETROIT, May 15 — Ron Gettelfinger, president of the union, is a man of few words, so it is never easy to be sure what he is thinking. Skip to next paragraph Ron Gettelfinger, the U.A.W. chief, at a news briefing Monday. That is especially true now because what little he has said about the sale of the Chrysler Group to Cerberus Capital Management, a private investment firm, has been contradictory. A month ago, he warned that a private buyer might “strip and flip” Chrysler for profit, ignoring the best interests of its unionized workers, whose job security and benefits he is trying to protect. But on Monday, Mr. Gettelfinger said the sale was the solution that best met his members’ needs. That sharp reversal might threaten the credibility of a different labor leader in a similarly delicate spot, analysts noted. But those who know Mr. Gettelfinger, 62, say his actions are more important than his words. What he has managed to do, by all accounts, is to strike a balance. He must appear strong to his members, whose ranks have been thinned by the crisis facing Detroit. But he also has to help the automakers get back on stable ground or risk further cutbacks at , Chrysler and the parts suppliers that the union represents. “There are no good options on the bargaining table now,” said Gary N. Chaison, professor of industrial relations at Clark University in Worcester, Mass. “There are only bad options and worse options.” said that its Chrysler division lost $1.98 billion in the first quarter, including revamping charges, in contrast to a profit of $857 million in the period a year earlier. (Daimler earned $2.67 billion in the first three months of the year, more than double its profit the year before.) The situation in Detroit arguably puts more pressure on Mr. Gettelfinger than any other U.A.W. president has faced since the early 1980s, when the union was forced to grant concessions to each of the auto companies in order to help save them. That could explain his testiness on Monday, when Mr. Gettelfinger appeared to run out of patience with journalists pushing him to explain why he now supported the sale when he had insisted that the union preferred to see Chrysler remain part of DaimlerChrysler. “O.K., I’m going to go over this one last time,” he said, interrupting a questioner. “The status quo was off the table. Cerberus was the only company that we discussed” with DaimlerChrysler’s chief executive, Dieter Zetsche, at a four-hour meeting in Stuttgart, Germany, on Saturday. Mr. Gettelfinger added, “The decision was made before we ever got there” that the meeting would focus only on the Cerberus bid. Given that, he said, the union saw little choice but to support it. But there appears to have been another reason for the reversal: the presence as a consultant to Cerberus of a former Chrysler president, Wolfgang Bernhard, people familiar with Mr. Gettelfinger’s thinking said Tuesday. Mr. Gettelfinger, who sits on the DaimlerChrysler supervisory board, got to know Mr. Bernhard before the executive left Chrysler for jobs at Mercedes-Benz and With Mr. Bernhard back on the scene, Mr. Gettelfinger felt confident that he had someone he could work with at Cerberus. Mr. Gettelfinger alluded to that Monday, without mentioning Mr. Bernhard by name. “There were a lot of things that we were concerned about,” the union leader said, “but based on everything that we heard, we were confident enough to say that we support this transaction.” Mr. Bernhard met Tuesday with the Chrysler chief executive, Thomas W. LaSorda, who said that Mr. Bernhard would serve as a “key adviser,” but not join Chrysler’s management. “I’ll use him when I need him,” Mr. LaSorda said. Mr. Gettelfinger met Tuesday with the chief executive of Cerberus, Stephen A. Feinberg, who spoke to Chrysler officials on Monday night and explained the private equity firm’s plans for the automaker. Personal connections count for a lot with Mr. Gettelfinger, whose first job was at Ford’s truck plant in Louisville, Ky., and whose voice has Southern traces. In public, his bearing can be reserved, although he is affectionate with his fellow union members, exchanging warm handshakes and manly hugs and greeting members as “brother” or “sister” in the union movement’s tradition. His courtliness is in sharp contrast to his sometimes profane predecessor, the late Stephen P. Yokich, who was known for his public jabs. Mr. Gettelfinger has more in common, in terms of operating style, with Owen Bieber, the union’s president from 1983 to 1995. The more formal bearing of those two men contrasted with the ebullient manner of Douglas A. Fraser, who ran the union more than a quarter-century ago. Mr. Fraser had been the only U.A.W. president since the end of World War II to make significant contract concessions until Mr. Gettelfinger, who agreed to landmark deals at G.M. and Ford in the last two years aimed at reducing health care costs. Mr. Gettelfinger has offered other forms of cooperation to the struggling car companies, although he might not like to see it characterized that way. Last year, he reached agreements with G.M., Ford and Chrysler to provide buyouts and other retirement incentives up to $140,000 to tens of thousands of workers. Many would have lost their jobs anyway because of cuts of nearly 70,000 positions announced by the companies, which are closing more than two dozen factories in the next few years. Because of those deals, the union has not fought the plant-closing decisions, which at an earlier time might have prompted strikes in an effort to keep them open. Mr. Gettelfinger has managed to protect wages and benefits at the auto parts maker , which had demanded deep cuts under bankruptcy protection. Workers there are still earning the $28 an hour in wages and receiving the same pensions and health care benefits they got before the company filed for Chapter 11 status. With contract talks now two months away, it looks unlikely that Delphi workers will give up anything before the union and the automakers sit down to discuss a new national agreement. Those talks are shaping up as less of a showdown than a forum that will allow Mr. Gettelfinger and the companies to forge a path that will take them through the next phase of the industry’s wrenching overhaul. “You have to adapt to the playing field that you’re on, not the playing field that you wish to be on,” said David Gregory, a labor law expert at ANALYSIS; In Deal, a Test for the U.A.W. Chief Warns Automakers That U.A.W. Won't Budge on Health Care or Jobs Bank Auto Union Head Vows Hard Line Against Concessions DETROIT'S SLUMP COULD BREAK UP CHRYSLER GROUP &#x00bb; MOST POPULAR - BUSINESS Economix: Truth, Fiction and Lou Dobbs Bumped Fliers and No Plan B In India, Grandma Cooks, They Deliver Is Wal-Mart Too Cheap for Its Own Good? Advertising: Telling India&#8217;s Modern Women They Have Power, Even Over Their Skin Tone Wachovia to Buy A.G. Edwards for $6.8 Billion Ernst & Young Won&#8217;t Face Criminal Charges Europe Pushes to Get Fuel From Fields Melamine From U.S. Put in Feed Lens Fluid Maker Says Link to Infection Unsolved Fiction and Lou Dobbs Lawmakers Push for Big Subsidies for Coal Process Not to See the Fallen Is No Favor The High Price of Creating Free Ads Apple's Lesson for Sony's Stores: Just Connect More Than Ever, It Pays to Be the Top Executive Is Wal-Mart Too Cheap for Its Own Good? Test of Drug for Diabetes in Jeopardy Now, Spitzer Is Warming to Wall St. Grandma Cooks, They Deliver million dollar homes in Florida, Wyoming and California Also in Real Estate: U.S. Virgin Islands Home & Garden &#x00bb; Art &