his service’s biggest potential drawbacks. Callers do not see each other’s real cellphone numbers, which preserves some of their anonymity. They can also block calls to prevent pests from turning into stalkers. Mr. Waterson said that SameLane would not promote dangerous driving. The first set of advertisements for the service (to be broadcast on talk radio stations in and around Atlanta, Los Angeles, San Francisco and Washington) will encourage drivers to make calls only when their vehicles are not in motion. Those admonishments are likely to fall on deaf ears given how much time drivers already spend chatting on their phones, analysts said. Indeed, the service may lead people to reach for their cellphones instead of making obscene gestures at reckless drivers. “There’s some dangerous potential for incidents of road rage with this,” said David Alexander, an analyst in the automotive systems group at ABI Research of Oyster Bay, N.Y. “It’s being publicized as a social service, but what about the guy that cuts in front of you?” SameLane is not the first service to try to connect drivers. lets drivers post personal profiles online that others who spot their bumper stickers can view later. A variety of satellite-based services helps companies and their drivers communicate with each other. The CB radio created communities of drivers decades ago. But those radios broadcast one person to many people. By contrast, SameLane is a one-to-one service that will need thousands of customers if drivers are to have a decent chance to meet others on the road, said Carmi Levy, an analyst at Info-Tech Research Group of London, Ontario. Charging drivers $1.99 a minute will not encourage people to sign up, he added. Still, online services like MySpace and Facebook have defied skeptics and are very popular with young people, so one cannot fault Mr. Waterson for trying to replicate their success in the automotive industry, said Josh Bernoff, an analyst who tracks social networks for Forrest