http://www.nytimes.com/2007/05/29/nyregion/29ink.html?ex=1338091200&en=eb3c5432c7633ddd&ei=5088&partner=rssnyt&emc=rss Turning Grease to Fuel, and Despair to Hope - Grease to Fuel, and Despair to Hope Earl Wilson/The grease is pumped to a truck that will take it to the North American Biofuels Company on Long Island. It will become diesel fuel. 2007 The back entrance to Barbounia, a restaurant on Park Avenue South, was open and Joseph Presswood dragged out a 55-gallon barrel of cooking oil. He plunged a vacuum hose into the grease as Edgar Rivera flipped on a switch. Thick brown liquid bubbled up through the hose to a container in a truck parked on 20th Street. Skip to next paragraph Earl Wilson/The Ross, a worker for RWA Natural Resource Recovery, picks up used cooking oil at restaurant. Earl Wilson/The Rivera, another RWA worker. After two minutes, all that was left at the bottom of the barrel was an errant appetizer plate, a rock and an uncooked squid that never made it onto a plate of fried calamari. “You can’t just throw grease away,” said Lester Ross, 42, their supervisor. Mr. Ross, Mr. Presswood and Mr. Rivera are employees of RWA Natural Resource Recovery, which is part of Doe Fund Inc.’s Ready, Willing and Able Community Improvement Project, an organization that employs homeless people, many of them former drug addicts or people who have been behind bars. RWA Natural Resource Recovery, a nonprofit group, collects grease from restaurants free and sells it to North American Biofuels Company, a plant in Bohemia, on Long Island, that converts it to diesel fuel. On this day, the men in green jumpsuits had already collected 360 gallons of grease from the ESPN Zone, a restaurant in Times Square. Despite the slippery grime, the stains and the heavy lifting, they all were grateful that they had jobs. Mr. Ross, a former heroin addict, was one of the first workers in the grease-recovery program, which was started in December. “This stuff is dirty,” said Mr. Ross, who earns $13 an hour; Mr. Rivera and Mr. Presswood each make $8 an hour. His face was drenched in sweat and his latex gloves were greasy, but he was content. “I like being a pioneer,” he said. Mr. Presswood, 41, who had been homeless and a cocaine addict, and Mr. Rivera, 40, who had come to the program from jail, seemed pleased to be earning money at a regular job. When the program began, it had three employees, who collected 997 gallons of grease in December. It has grown to six employees, who collected 14,435 gallons in April, said Jonathan Steiman, the project’s manager. There are 154 clients, but the list increases daily, he said. Instead of making the trip to the Long Island plant once a week, workers now make trips every three days or so. In the meantime, the grease is taken to a storage unit in Hunts Point in the Bronx, but is not kept there for long. “You don’t want the stuff sitting,” Mr. Steiman said. While a big part of the project is to recycle restaurant waste into something usable, the truck hauling the grease does not run on biodiesel fuel. With just one truck, the operation is too small to finance the cost of retrofitting the vehicle. Still, Mr. Ross predicted, “One day, we’ll be picking up grease all over the city.” York Region It Takes More Than Veggies to Make a Kitchen Green GREEN TECH; Restaurant Problem Becomes a Solution Starbucks Will Use Cups With 10% Recycled Paper URBAN TACTICS; Grease Is the Word Recycling of Waste Materials Oil (Petroleum) and Gasoline York Region &#x00bb; De Court Memo: Oral Dissents Give Ginsburg a New Voice on Court Comedy Business Turns to the Web Fiction and Lou Dobbs Lawmakers Push for Big Subsidies for Coal Process Google million dollar homes in Florida, Wyoming and California Also in Real Estate: U.S. Virgin Islands 50% off Times delivery. Home & Garden &#x00bb; Art & Design &#x00bb; Sarkozys: The French Kennedys? Phil Spector’s Long and Winding Road The Dirty Water Underground An Animated Film by Jeff Scher Artist Sets Up House(s) at the Grand Palais
http://www.nytimes.com/2007/05/29/nyregion/29ink.html?ex=1338091200&en=eb3c5432c7633ddd&ei=5088&partner=rssnyt&emc=rss Turning Grease to Fuel, and Despair to Hope Grease to Fuel, and Despair to Hope Earl Wilson/The grease is pumped to a truck that will take it to the North American Biofuels Company on Long Island. It will become diesel fuel. 2007 The back entrance to Barbounia, a restaurant on Park Avenue South, was open and Joseph Presswood dragged out a 55-gallon barrel of cooking oil. He plunged a vacuum hose into the grease as Edgar Rivera flipped on a switch. Thick brown liquid bubbled up through the hose to a container in a truck parked on 20th Street. Wilson/The Ross, a worker for RWA Natural Resource Recovery, picks up used cooking oil at restaurant. Earl Wilson/The Rivera, another RWA worker. After two minutes, all that was left at the bottom of the barrel was an errant appetizer plate, a rock and an uncooked squid that never made it onto a plate of fried calamari. “You can’t just throw grease away,” said Lester Ross, 42, their supervisor. Mr. Ross, Mr. Presswood and Mr. Rivera are employees of RWA Natural Resource Recovery, which is part of Doe Fund Inc.’s Ready, Willing and Able Community Improvement Project, an organization that employs homeless people, many of them former drug addicts or people who have been behind bars. RWA Natural Resource Recovery, a nonprofit group, collects grease from restaurants free and sells it to North American Biofuels Company, a plant in Bohemia, on Long Island, that converts it to diesel fuel. On this day, the men in green jumpsuits had already collected 360 gallons of grease from the ESPN Zone, a restaurant in Times Square. Despite the slippery grime, the stains and the heavy lifting, they all were grateful that they had jobs. Mr. Ross, a former heroin addict, was one of the first workers in the grease-recovery program, which was started in December. “This stuff is dirty,” said Mr. Ross, who earns $13 an hour; Mr. Rivera and Mr. Presswood each make $8 an hour. His face was drenched in sweat and his latex gloves were greasy, but he was content. “I like being a pioneer,” he said. Mr. Presswood, 41, who had been homeless and a cocaine addict, and Mr. Rivera, 40, who had come to the program from jail, seemed pleased to be earning money at a regular job. When the program began, it had three employees, who collected 997 gallons of grease in December. It has grown to six employees, who collected 14,435 gallons in April, said Jonathan Steiman, the project’s manager. There are 154 clients, but the list increases daily, he said. Instead of making the trip to the Long Island plant once a week, workers now make trips every three days or so. In the meantime, the grease is taken to a storage unit in Hunts Point in the Bronx, but is not kept there for long. “You don’t want the stuff sitting,” Mr. Steiman said. While a big part of the project is to recycle restaurant waste into something usable, the truck hauling the grease does not run on biodiesel fuel. With just one truck, the operation is too small to finance the cost of retrofitting the vehicle. Still, Mr. Ross predicted, “One day, we’ll be picking up grease all over the city.” York Region It Takes More Than Veggies to Make a Kitchen Green GREEN TECH; Restaurant Problem Becomes a Solution Starbucks Will Use Cups With 10% Recycled Paper URBAN TACTICS; Grease Is the Word Recycling of Waste Materials Oil (Petroleum) and Gasoline York Region &#x00bb; De Contributor: Fliers and No Plan B Economix: Times delivery.
